{[%evp 0,43,19,31,14,-14,43,38,37,37,37,11,13,-21,7,6,10,10,18,0,15,25,27,13, 24,22,17,22,16,21,23,0,12,13,25,-34,-2,-55,16,32,47,51,79,77,71,67]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 {Sometimes KID players omit the standard move 4...d6 and play} O-O {inviting White to extend his centre with 5.e5. However, we can simply proceed with the standard development scheme instead.} 5. Nge2 {This is usually considered merely as a surprise weapon against the KID, but it actually contains more venom than it might seem. I was quite sceptical about it at first because the knight does not seem to belong on g3 square when Black already has a pawn on g6. However, one of my students had great results with this system (often called Hungarian system) as White, so I decided to check it more deeply. After careful analysis, I came to the conclusion that this is indeed a very playable system for White that could even form a base for a long-term repertoire and not only a temporary weapon. Black needs to show very good home preparation not to be worse out of the opening, which can be seen in the analysis below.} ( {In case of} 6. e5 Ne8 { Black undermines the center with ...d6, ...c5 and the arising positions are not so clear.}  ) c6 {This is the point behind omitting the d6 move, Black plays directly for ... d7-d5 and later ...Nf6-e4. This idea can be effective against several other white setups, such as the classical one with the knight on f3. However, after} 6. Ng3 $1 { Black's idea loses sting because after} d5 7. e5 {the knight cannot reach e4-square, so it has to retreat} Ne8 {This is a good thing for White as Black is quite passive. First, we play} 8. cxd5 {to clarify the pawn structure in the centre and stabilize our space advantage.} cxd5 {At this point, White can choose from two reasonable approaches.} 9. h4 $5 {Aggressive approach is principled because White has the space advantage on the kingside and Black needs many moves to obtain counterplay.} ( {A more positional approach is} 10. Be2 f6 11. f4 $14 {The ability to push the f-pawn is a nice circumstance with the knight on g3 instead of the usual f3, as we will see on many other occasions, as well.}  ) Nc6 {This move was played by KID specialist E. Gufeld,} ( h5 {should probably be played, but it also looks scary for Black as it leaves many weaknesses.}  ) {but White can organize a strong attack with} 10. h5 Nc7 11. f4 e6 12. Be3 b6 13. Qg4 $18  *

