{[%evp 0,43,19,31,14,-14,43,38,37,37,37,11,13,-21,7,6,10,10,18,0,15,25,27,13, 24,22,17,22,16,21,23,0,12,13,25,-34,-2,-55,16,32,47,51,79,77,71,67]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nge2 {Black also has some extra options delaying castling. The most common one is} Nbd7 6. Ng3 e5 7. d5 a5 {securing c5-outpost.} ( {Another typical move is} h5 { targeting the knight on g3. However, with the rook still on h8, the extra idea is to trade the dark-squared bishops via h6. The mystery of the KID is that we develop the bishop to g7, then voluntarily block it with e5, only to try to reactivate it again throughout the game.} 8. Bd3 h4 ( Bh6 {is also possible at once, according to the previous comments. White enjoys a slight plus thanks to the space advantage as we can see in the following logical line:} 9. Bxh6 Rxh6 10. Qd2 Rh8 11. h4 Nc5 12. Bc2 a5 13. O-O-O Bd7 14. f3 $14  ) 9. Nge2 a5 10. h3 Nc5 11. Bc2 Bd7 12. Rb1 { preparing b4-break with Be3, a3, etc. The bishop is useful on c2 for that purpose, taking important squares a4 and b3 under control.}  ) ( Nc5 {runs into} 8. b4 {of course.}  ) 8. Bd3 {is a more active square than e2, also providing support to the e4-pawn, so why not play it here when Black signalled that the knight is headed to c5-square?} Nc5 9. Bc2 O-O 10. O-O Bd7 {This is all normal development from both sides. White's standard plan is to prepare b2-b4 with} 11. Rb1 {In response, Black typically initiates kingside play with} h5 {and now a logical continuation would be} 12. Bg5 Qe8 13. Nge2 Nh7 14. Be3 f5 15. exf5 gxf5 {We have reached a critical position in which both sides have achieved something. In one of the main lines after 5...0-0 and 6...e5, we analyze a seemingly anti-positional idea:} 16. Bxc5 $5 dxc5 {which seems to be working well here, too, because we can open the centre with} 17. d6 $1 cxd6 ( c6 18. Na4 {and White wins the pawn on c5.}  ) 18. Qxd6 $14 {Black has some clear weaknesses, so White's position is for preference. That said, Black has a decent compensation in the view of the bishop pair and the mobile pawn centre.}  *

