{[%evp 0,43,19,31,14,-14,43,38,37,37,37,11,13,-21,7,6,10,10,18,0,15,25,27,13, 24,22,17,22,16,21,23,0,12,13,25,-34,-2,-55,16,32,47,51,79,77,71,67]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nge2 c6 6. Ng3 a6 {is another flexible setup that can be played against many KID variations, often as a way to get out of the book and just get a game. The idea is, of course, to prepare ...b7-b5. I suggest that we continue according to our usual plan with} 7. Be2 ( 8. a4 {is also possible, stopping 7...b5, but it is already a concession as it gives Black an outpost on b4 after} a5  ) b5 8. O-O O-O 9. f4 {In many variations of this system, this is a logical move to siege the centre and take the initiative on the kingside. In this position, it is quite principled since Black played quite passively with his central pawns.} bxc4 ( e5 {looked a bit loose to me at first, but it turns out to be a reasonable move. White's best reply is} 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. f5 $14 {The arising pawn structure is favourable for White.}  ) 10. e5 $1 {This is the point.} ( 11. Bxc4 $6 {allows Black to fully demonstrate the point of the plan started with a6, c6, b5, namely:} d5 $132 {and the d4-pawn may become weak soon.}  ) Nd5 11. Bxc4 {There is no ...d6-d5 now and White controls the centre.} dxe5 12. dxe5 $146 {This is more accurate than the other recapture that has been seen in practice.} ( 13. fxe5 Be6 {and Black may break with ...c5 at some point.}  ) Be6 13. Bb3 $14 { White has a better pawn structure and controls more space. He should have better chances in the positional battle ahead.}  *

