{[%evp 0,43,19,31,14,-14,43,38,37,37,37,11,13,-21,7,6,10,10,18,0,15,25,27,13, 24,22,17,22,16,21,23,0,12,13,25,-34,-2,-55,16,32,47,51,79,77,71,67]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nge2 O-O 6. Ng3 { The fact that we develop the knight to a square which is limited by the pawn on g6 might seem anti-positional. However, the position of the knight on g3 contains several benefits. Firstly, it gives protection to the e4 pawn, which is very important in the KID. Secondly, it puts pressure the f5-square, which becomes important in 6...e5 and 6...c5 lines alike. Thirdly, it supports the aggressive h2-h4-h5 push in many lines. And finally, it is not in the way of the f-pawn, which allows White to quickly pursue the attack with the f-pawn in some lines, especially in the Benoni structure.} {The main alternative is} c5 7. d5 e6 ( e5 {is a somewhat passive alternative, leading into a closed type of position. White can continue similarly to the 6...e5 variation:} 8. Be2 Nbd7 ( Ne8 9. h4 f5 10. exf5 gxf5 11. Nh5 $36 { This is another thematic idea with the knight on g3.}  ) 9. h4 $1 h5 10. Bg5 $14 {preparing f3-g4 in the future.}  ) 8. Be2 exd5 9. cxd5 {leading into the typical Benoni structure. As a matter of fact, this position can also arise from the Nge2 variation of the Benoni defence. The knight is placed well on g3 as it protects the potentially vulnerable e4-pawn, while also not being in the way of the f-pawn, which becomes important in the middlegame.} ( {The alternative} 10. exd5 {a pet line of GM Pavel Tregubov, leads into a safe symmetrical position with space advantage for White. Black's best plan is probably} Nbd7 11. O-O Ne8 $13 { preparing ...f5 to grab some space, followed by ...Nc7, and ...Nf6. Compared to 9.cxd5, this is not such an exciting position for White.}  ) {Black usually employ one of two classical ideas:} a6 ( {or} Na6 10. O-O Nc7 11. a4 {It is important to keep the ...b5-break under control for as long as possible, so that we can focus on the central break f4-e5.} a6 ( {Another possibility seen in practice is} Nd7 {opening the dark-squared bishop and avoiding the Bg5 pin. However, this is also a rather slow plan.} 12. Bf4 {This is a clever move. Instead of playing the thematic f2-f4, we first develop the bishop, provoking} Ne5 {which can later be hit by a pawn with a tempo.} 13. Qd2 h5 14. h3 {taking g4-square under control and stopping black pawn from getting to h3.} Bd7 ( {we are not worried about} h4 15. Nh1 {which does look a bit awkward, but the point it that after f2-f4, the knight eventually gets to a good square f2.}  ) 15. Rae1 {we fully mobilize our pieces on the kingside in preparation for f2-f4.} a6 16. Bh6 $36 { It is good to weaken black king by exchanging dark-squared bishop before proceeding with f2-f4, etc. Black's queenside counterplay is too slow.}  ) 12. Bg5 $1 {This pin is the key in many lines. Black is practically forced to weaken the kingside with} h6 ( {because in case of} Rb8 13. f4 { already poses a very strong threat.}  ) 13. Be3 Re8 {This is a standard useful Benoni move.} ( Rb8 {is inaccurate in the view of} 14. e5 dxe5 15. Bxc5 $36 Re8 16. Bb6 $16  ) 14. Qd2 {It turns out that with Bg5 we won a tempo to develop the queen, and also weakened black kingside in the process.} Kh7 ( h5 {further weakens black kingside since 15...h4 can be easily prevented by} 15. Bg5 {The pin is unpleasant now. Black is in trouble after} Qd7 16. f4 Nh7 17. Bh4 $16 {White has a huge advantage with e5-break to come:} Rb8 18. e5 dxe5 19. f5 $1 $18 { The point. This is a classical idea to block black pieces and take control over the e4-outpost, following up with a kingside attack.}  ) 15. h3 {This is an important prophylactic move. It might seem slow, but as we will see, White has just enough time to execute the central break.} ( {In case of} 16. f4 {Black is happy to trade the light-squared bishop with} Bg4 {In general, this is true in most Benoni positions.}  ) Rb8 16. f4 b5 {It seems like Black got his typical counterplay in time but after} 17. e5 $1 {White keeps the initiative.} b4 {The critical continuation.} ( {After} dxe5 18. d6 {is the point, and if} b4 {then} 19. Nce4 $36  ) 18. Nce4 Nfxd5 {Black won a pawn, but White has a fantastic quiet move to keep the initiative:} 19. Rad1 $1 { Using the pin on the d-file, White renews the threat to d6-pawn.} ( {Black relied on the fact that} 20. Nxd6 $2 {does not work because of} Nxe3 21. Qxe3 Qxd6 $19  ) dxe5 ( Nxe3 20. Qxe3 d5 21. Qxc5 $18  ) 20. f5 $18 { A remarkable approach - White is 2 pawns down but has a powerful attack coming as all his pieces are mobilized and Black cannot move his pieces.}  ) 10. a4 Nbd7 {This is the main move.} ( h5 {is a tempting alternative, but also quite a committal as it weakens the kingside. This often backfires as g5 square and g6-pawn become vulnerable.} 11. Bg5 {We should take the opportunity to play this move whenever possible} Qc7 12. Qd2 Nbd7 13. O-O Rb8 14. f4 ( {Even possible is the engine's suggestion} 15. e5 $5 Nxe5 ( dxe5 16. d6  ) 16. f4 { giving up a pawn to speed up kingside attack. However, the slower approach 14.f4 cannot be bad either.}  ) Nh7 15. Bh4 ( 16. Be7 $5 {is another engine idea. This time it is very subtle. The idea is to force black rook off the f-file, which might come in handy later when the f-file opens up.} Re8 17. Bh4 {and you could compare this to a similar position in 15. Bh4 main line to see whether the position of the rook on e8 is indeed worse for Black.}  ) c4 {This is Black's typical counterplay.} 16. Kh1 {It makes sense to hide the king from possible checks before moving on with the main plan.} b5 17. axb5 axb5 {Everything is ready for the standard break:} 18. e5 dxe5 19. f5 $36 {White has a typical unpleasant pressure for the sacrificed pawn with Nce4 to follow.}  ) 11. O-O Re8 {Most strong black players go for this position.} ( Rb8 {is a quicker way to prepare ...b7-b5.} 12. Bg5 {As in the variation Na6, we don't mind it if Black weakens his position with h6 now because the tempo can be regained with Qd2 soon.} Qc7 {The idea behind this move is not only to unpin but also to push ...c4 as a way to prepare ...b5 by blocking the light-squared bishop.} 13. Qd2 c4 14. Rac1 $1 {An interesting prophylactic idea, which is quite thematic with the queen on c7.} ( {In case of} 15. f4 h6 16. Bh4 b5 $13 {the usual break} 17. e5 dxe5 18. f5 {does not work in the view of} g5  ) b5 15. axb5 axb5 16. b4 { Blocking black pawns on the queenside by using the pin on the c-pawn.} Re8 ( {The tactical point is that in case of} cxb3 17. Nxb5 $16 { the d6-pawn falls and black passed pawn can be blocked fairly easily.}  ) 17. Kh1 $16 { We have a classical advantage for White here. We can slowly recentralize with Be3-d4, bring the rook over to the a-file and prepare f4-e5 in better circumstances. Also, the pawn on b5 is a long-term weakness.}  ) 12. h3 {This sensible move is not too popular in general, but it was played lately by a couple of strong GMs. It is useful prophylaxis as control of the g4-square comes in handy in many cases.} Rb8 {This is the most straightforward continuation, though some alternatives exist.} ( h5 {is typically answered by} 13. Bg5 Qc7 14. Qd2 Rb8 15. f4 Nh7 16. Bh4 c4 17. e5 dxe5 18. f5 $40 {which is pretty much a model game. White might just have a decisive attack.}  ) ( b6 {is a passive move with the point not to allow a4-a5.} 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bf4 $1 {This is a subtle retreat, with the idea to provoke 14...Ne5.} h5 {Indirectly defending d6-pawn.} ( {In case of} Ne5 {we play} 15. Be3 {when f2-f4 comes with a tempo}  ) {However, we can simply come back} 15. Bg5 $1 Qc7 16. Re1 {This quiet prophylactic move has been seen in a correspondence game.} ( {Although there was nothing wrong with} 17. f4 $5 {either.}  ) c4 17. Qb1 $1 {Another curious prophylactic idea from the same correspondence game.} Rb8 18. Rc1 $1 {This thematic manoeuvre to slow down black play on the queenside was the point behind the previous white move.} b5 19. axb5 axb5 20. b4 $16 { With the queenside safely blocked, White is fully in control of the position.}  ) 13. Bg5 Qc7 {It seems like Black does better not to move the h-pawn forward in most lines. Yet, this move allows White to play Qd2 and keep the bishop on g5 from where it exerts pressure on black position anyway.} ( {In case of} h6 14. Bf4 $1 {again, this provocative move is strong.} Ne5 ( Qe7 15. Re1 {Using x-ray motifs with black queen on e7.} h5 16. Bg5 Qf8 17. Qc2 $16 { Black is solid, but he has no active play (b5 is not working with e4-pawn so well defended) . White has a big space advantage and can potentially even manoeuvre the knight to the ideal square c4 via f1 and d2.}  ) 15. Qd2 Kh7 16. Be3 $36 { winning a tempo with f2-f4.}  ) 14. Qd2 c4 15. Rfc1 {This is the simplest approach, as seen in some similar lines previously.} b5 16. axb5 axb5 17. b4 cxb3 {The critical move, otherwise White is just positionally better.} 18. Nxb5 Qd8 {Here it is a bit more complicated than in similar lines that we have seen; White has to watch out for tactics with the b2-pawn. Yet, it seems like after} 19. Rab1 Nc5 20. Qf4 $16 {everything is under control.} b2 $140 21. Rxc5 $18  *

