{[%evp 0,43,19,31,14,-14,43,38,37,37,37,11,13,-21,7,6,10,10,18,0,15,25,27,13, 24,22,17,22,16,21,23,0,12,13,25,-34,-2,-55,16,32,47,51,79,77,71,67]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nge2 O-O 6. Ng3 e5 7. d5 a5 {This is the critical line, securing the important c5-outpost for the knight.} ( {We can see one advantage of having the knight on g3 in the line} Na6 8. Be2 Nc5 $6 { when} 9. b4 $1 {is possible since the e4-pawn is protected twice.}  ) ( Ne8 {is a logical attempt to push ...f5 as quickly as possible. Here it is important to respond with} 8. h4 $1 ( 9. Be2 {allows Black to play an interesting move} Qh4 {preparing a favourable exchange of dark-squared bishops on h6.}  ) f5 ( h5 {is also possible, but then ...f7-f5 is hardly an option for Black in the future. It is also important that we can continue developing normally with} 9. Be2 {since} Bf6 {is strongly met by} 10. Nf1 Bxh4 {(otherwise 11.g3)} 11. Bxh5 $1 $36  ) 9. exf5 gxf5 ( {If} Bxf5 {we can continue} 10. h5 $16 { with a clear strategic advantage.}  ) 10. Nh5 Bh8 {preserving the bishop at the cost of all black pieces being on the last rank!} ( {in case of} Nf6 {we even do not need to rush with the capture on g7, but we can rather pin the knight first with} 11. Bg5  ) 11. Bg5 Nf6 12. Qd2 {Simple development. We will castle queenside next and prepare the opening of the kingside.} Qe8 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6 14. O-O-O Qg6 15. f3 { getting ready for Bd3 and g2-g4. In a way, early ..f5 break backfires against Black because he is not well developed.}  ) ( c6 {is a part of the thematic KID strategy to create a play on the queenside. This discourages White from playing the typical h2-h4 because castling queenside becomes riskier with the open c-file. Instead, we can simply castle kingside and focus on queenside play using the space advantage.} 8. Be2 cxd5 9. cxd5 Nbd7 10. O-O a6 {The most popular approach for Black.} 11. Re1 {Played by GM Bologan, is a nice move to vacate f1-square for the knight and potentially reroute it to a better square than g3; for example Ng3-f1-d2/e3-c4.} h5 ( b5 {is met by} 12. b4 $14 { when a2-a4 usually exposes black queenside pawns as weak.}  ) 12. Bg5 Qe8 13. Nf1 Nh7 14. Be3 $14 {The knight is placed better on f1 than on g3 and White is ready for queenside play with Rc1, Qb3, Na4 etc. Meanwhile, it is not so easy for Black to organize active counterplay on the kingside quickly.}  ) 8. Be2 Na6 9. h4 {The key idea! However, this is not so much an attacking idea as in the Saemisch variation as it is a mix of positional and attacking approach.} h5 {This is the most natural and common reaction. A few KID players would allow White to push the pawn to h5.} 10. Bg5 {Important move a la Petrosian, pinning the knight and forcing Black to spend some time unpinning. Surprisingly, it is also setting up a tactical trap.} Qe8 ( Nc5 $2 {Over 80 games in database saw Black making this natural move, which is virtually a decisive mistake!} 11. Bxh5 $1 gxh5 12. Nxh5 $18 {White already has a crushing attack. The combination of the pin and destroyed pawn shield around the black king is too much for Black to handle.} Kh8 {stopping Qf3, is the most stubborn defence.} ( Ncd7 {is too passive.} 13. Qf3 Qe7 14. Rh3 $1 {Bringing more attackers to the party.} Kh7 15. Rg3 Rg8 16. Nd1 $18 { White had many ways to continue the attack, but rerouting the knight to f5 is the most decisive.}  ) 13. Nxf6 $1 {It is good that we can continue the attack with such simple means.} ( 14. Qf3 $2 {would run into} Bg4 $132 {which was the idea behind 12...Kh8.}  ) Bxf6 14. Qh5+ Kg8 ( Kg7 15. Qh6+  ) 15. Kd2 $1 {Connecting the rooks. We also keep the pin on f6 in a way since Bxg5 is never an option for Black. The main attacking idea is still to lift the rook to the third rank and g3.} Re8 ( Be7 16. Bh6 $18  ) 16. Rae1 Kf8 17. Re3 ( 18. Qh6+ Bg7  ) Bxg5 ( Ke7 18. Bxf6+ Kxf6 19. Qg5#  ) 18. hxg5 Ke7 {It looks like black king might escape, but White attacks with all his heavy pieces and Black is actually helpless.} 19. Rf3 Rf8 20. g6 $1 {Opening up the king.} Qe8 21. Qg5+ Kd7 22. Rh7 $18  ) 11. Qd2 {The long-term plan is to castle queenside and create conditions for kingside break with g4.} Nc5 12. f3 $1 { A very important move.} ( 13. O-O-O {as played by Carlsen against Radjabov, is not accurate because of} Ng4 $1 14. Bxg4 Bxg4 15. f3 Bd7 $13 { While the arising position is approximately equal, Black is slightly more comfortable. In practice, Black has also been doing very well in this position. The key is that the white light-squared bishop is a very important defensive piece as it supports our g2-g4 break and keeps the opponent's b5-break under control. Therefore, it is best not to give it up and 12.f3 is played for that reason.}  ) {Black has two main plans now: one on the kingside, the other on the queenside.} Bd7 {With this move, Black keeps developing and will try to create counterplay on the queenside.} ( {The kingside approach is} Nh7 {preparing ...f7-f5.} 13. Be3 {It is better to preserve the dark-squared bishop from exchange on h6.} f5 14. Bxc5 $146 {This is a new idea. Firstly, it is surprising because we just preserved the bishop from an exchange and now we voluntarily trade it. Secondly, it looks positionally suspicious. However, there is a concrete idea behind it.} ( {Previously played was} 15. exf5 gxf5 16. f4 Nf6 $13 {Kantor-Demchenko, 2017. The arising position is double-edged but very playable for Black.}  ) dxc5 15. Nb5 Qf7 {The critical move.} ( Qe7 {runs into} 16. d6 $1 {This is the key idea - to open the centre in order to exploit Black's vulnerable pawn structure.} ( 17. exf5 Bxf5 18. d6 cxd6 19. Qxd6 {is most likely just a transposition}  ) cxd6 17. exf5 Bxf5 ( gxf5 {seems inferior because of} 18. Nxh5  ) 18. Qxd6 Rae8 19. Nxf5 gxf5 20. O-O-O $16 { White has a clearly favourable position, although Black is not without resources thanks to the control of the dark squares.}  ) 16. exf5 {an important exchange to expose the h5-pawn} gxf5 ( Bxf5 17. O-O-O $16  ) 17. f4 $1 {This critical move leads to a complicated position which should be preferable for White.} exf4 18. Nxh5 Be5 {The long diagonal is open for KID bishop, but White has accomplished some things as well - the black king is exposed and black pawn structure is worse.} 19. O-O-O Nf6 20. Nxf6+ Qxf6 21. Bh5 $1 Bd7 22. Qe2 $14  ) 13. O-O-O a4 14. Kb1 Qb8 {This is an interesting manoeuvre, 4 games have been played with this position. However, it is objectively suspicious because it leaves black kingside more exposed.} 15. Nf1 {is the most logical continuation, preparing the thematic g4 break.} Nh7 {The best reaction.} ( {The straightforward continuation} Qa7 {is strongly met by} 16. g4 $1 hxg4 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 ( gxf3 18. Bxg7  ) 18. fxg4 Qb6 19. Ne3 {Instead of attacking directly, White has a positional idea in mind:} Kg7 20. g5 Bd8 21. Bg4 $16 {After the exchange of light-squared bishop, White is strategically superior. One correspondence game saw a desperation sacrifice:} Bxg4 22. Nxg4 a3 23. b3 Nxb3 24. axb3 Qxb3+ 25. Ka1 Qxc4 26. Rh3 { White king is safe, though.} b5 27. h5 b4 28. hxg6 fxg6 29. Nf6 {and Black resigned.}  ) 16. Be3 a3 {The following correspondence game lead to complicated play with many subtle ideas for both sides:} 17. g4 ( 18. b3 {is the safest reply, but the problem is that after} f5 19. g4 f4 $13 {the position is too closed.}  ) hxg4 18. b3 $1 {This seems like a somewhat mysterious move, but White can afford to sacrifice a pawn to open a file for an attack on the kingside.} ( 19. Bxc5 dxc5 20. fxg4 axb2 21. g5 { would lead to a complicated position. The pawn on b2 protects white king in a way and White has attacking ideas on the kingside.}  ) f5 ( gxf3 19. Bxf3 {is too risky for Black, obviously.}  ) 19. fxg4 fxg4 20. h5 {This looks very nice for White, but Black has a strong thematic sacrifice} Rf4 $1 21. hxg6 Ng5 22. Ng3 $13 { with a complicated position that ended in a draw in the game Varkentin, W (2311) -Klengel, M (2316) ICCF email 2017 1/2-1/2 (33)}  *

